          "workflow": {
            "version": "1.0",
            "_note": "Phase 0 (Orchestrator Overhaul). This node is the active rulebook for routing, intake-question selection, confidence gating, and pricing -- not passive documentation. Every entry path (Catalog browse, Other-tile tap, free-text SmartQuote) must produce a BookingContext and pass it through executeWorkflow(context, db), which walks these steps in order. See Phase 5.5's _archaeology_notes on individual rules below for the specific real bug each rule exists to prevent -- these were extracted from actual hardcoded logic found and fixed during the architecture-audit sessions, not invented speculatively.",
            "required_fields": [
              "services",
              "dynamic_services",
              "intake_modules",
              "smart_tags",
              "global_rules",
              "checkout_states",
              "intent_mappings",
              "confidence_escalation",
              "pricing_formulas",
              "materials_catalog"
            ],
            "steps": [
              {
                "id": "resolve_entity",
                "operation": "lookup",
                "_note": "Resolves BookingContext -> a concrete service or dynamic_service entity. For entry='catalog' or 'other_tile', selectedServiceId/selectedGroupId already pin this down directly. For entry='free_text', this step delegates to intent_mappings.objects keyword/synonym matching (NOT a hardcoded keyword map -- see the architecture-audit finding that resolveGroupFromIntent's hardcoded rules and intent_mappings.objects were two parallel, partially-overlapping systems; this workflow makes intent_mappings.objects the single real source going forward).",
                "sources": [
                  "context.selectedServiceId",
                  "context.selectedGroupId",
                  "context.nlpIntent.recommendedSku",
                  "intent_mappings.objects"
                ],
                "fallback": {
                  "route_to": "intent_mappings.default_fallback",
                  "_warn": "no entity resolved with sufficient confidence"
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "compute_variability_flags",
                "operation": "modify",
                "_note": "Computes a small set of NAMED, independently-auditable booleans -- NOT a single opaque chainIsQtyOnly flag. Archaeology finding: the legacy chainIsQtyOnly check was too coarse to correctly handle behavior.bypass_intake services, 3 of which (high_ceiling_bulb_replacement, shower_head_replacement, tub_spout_replacement) have ONE real, price-affecting, non-quantity question that must still be asked even though the service is otherwise flagged for minimal friction. A single boolean cannot represent that distinction; named, separate flags can.",
                "produces": {
                  "chain_is_pure_quantity": "true only if every module in the resolved intake_chain is a recognized quantity-style module (item_count, count, hybrid_qty, global_quantity)",
                  "chain_is_single_simple_question": "true if the chain has exactly one module AND that module is item_count_template (a banded quantity question) -- distinct from chain_is_pure_quantity, since item_count_template is NOT in the legacy quantity-module set but is still simple enough to bypass extensive intake when paired with behavior.bypass_intake",
                  "chain_has_real_non_quantity_question": "true if the chain contains any module that is neither a quantity-style module nor item_count_template -- when true, intake bypass rules MUST still surface that question; bypassing it would silently drop a real, price-affecting answer",
                  "all_visible_real_questions_answered": "true once every currently-visible (per _isModVisible) non-quantity module has a real answer in BookingContext.answers"
                }
              },
              {
                "id": "compose_intake_chain",
                "operation": "compose",
                "_note": "Builds the final, real list of intake questions to ask: entity.intake_chain (the named modules) + global_rules.force_modules_by_variability[entity.confidence_strategy._variability_tier] (universal logistics/height questions, injected only when not already present) + then-branch targets unlocked by already-given answers. Archaeology finding: an earlier version of this logic (S._forceModules) was SET but never CONSUMED in the legacy curated-intake renderer -- confirmed and fixed mid-session; this step makes that consumption a mandatory, auditable part of the workflow rather than something that can silently regress again.",
                "sources": [
                  "entity.intake_chain",
                  "global_rules.force_modules_by_variability",
                  "intake_modules.*.then"
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": "apply_location_hints",
                "operation": "modify",
                "_note": "Archaeology finding (direct feedback during the session): the location chip/NLP-extracted location was being treated as cosmetic filler/notes despite carrying real, derivable intent (a 'front door' implies solid-core, a 'bedroom door' implies hollow-core; a 'toilet' near 'guest bedroom' is genuinely ambiguous and must NOT be guessed). This step pre-fills an intake answer ONLY when context.extractedLocation matches exactly one client_response[*].location_hints entry for a given module -- never when zero or multiple answers claim the same location, and never overriding an answer the user already gave.",
                "sources": [
                  "context.extractedLocation",
                  "intake_modules.*.client_response.*.location_hints"
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": "compute_confidence",
                "operation": "merge",
                "_note": "Archaeology finding: the legacy curated-intake renderer used a hardcoded tagBonus (+5 skilled / +10 specialized, ADDED TO THE SCORE) instead of global_rules.confidence_escalation's real +15/+30 deltas (which RAISE THE BAR). These are mechanically different operations that were both firing in the same wrong direction -- confirmed via direct trace to make the Estimate button enable roughly 20 points too early for a real service (flatscreen_mounting_standard + #brick_wall: bar should rise 50->65, legacy code left it at 50 while also inflating the score). This step performs ONLY the bar-raising operation (confidence_escalation), and a separate, additive scoring step (base_confidence + module gains + NLP match confidence) computes the score independently -- the two must never be conflated into one number again.",
                "sources": [
                  "entity.confidence_strategy",
                  "global_rules.confidence_escalation",
                  "context.activeTagIds",
                  "context.nlpIntent._matchConfidence"
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": "select_ui_template",
                "operation": "condition_map",
                "_note": "See ui_template_matrix below -- this is the corrected version of Phase 3's example, using the named flags from compute_variability_flags instead of a single chainIsQtyOnly boolean.",
                "ref": "ui_template_matrix"
              },
              {
                "id": "merge_materials_estimate",
                "operation": "merge",
                "_note": "Archaeology finding (post-session audit): 51 services have real services.*.required_materials and 35 have optional_materials, referencing real materials_catalog SKUs with real prices and a real markup_percent (confirmed uniformly 20% in global_rules.surcharges) -- NONE of which is read at runtime; every materials display reads the separate, often-stale default_estimates.materials.min/max instead (confirmed 3 real services, e.g. dishwasher_repair, where the legacy number and the catalog-derived number would genuinely differ). Resolution, NOT deletion (Chesterton's Fence: default_estimates.materials.note frequently carries real, business-meaningful customer-facing explanation -- e.g. dishwasher_repair's 'Exact part cost cannot be determined before diagnosis' -- that has no equivalent in the catalog data and must be preserved): when required_materials/optional_materials is non-empty, compute min = sum(required SKU prices * (1+markup)), max = min + sum(optional SKU prices * (1+markup)), and use this as the authoritative materials range -- but ALWAYS carry forward default_estimates.materials.note verbatim if present, regardless of which range won.",
                "sources": [
                  "entity.required_materials",
                  "entity.optional_materials",
                  "materials_catalog",
                  "global_rules.surcharges.materials_markup_percent",
                  "entity.default_estimates.materials.note"
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": "compute_quote",
                "operation": "calculate",
                "_note": "Invokes the SINGLE unified pricing function for every entry path -- no separate _computePrice. Archaeology finding: the legacy Catalog-browse path's _computePrice never included global_rules.surcharges.dispatch_fee at all, while the SmartQuote path's computeUnifiedQuote always did -- the exact same service could quote differently by the full dispatch fee ($45) depending on which UI entry point was tapped. Confirmed and fixed mid-session by adding the fee to _computePrice directly (a stopgap); this workflow's real fix is that _computePrice no longer exists as a separate function at all once Phase 6 lands -- every entry path reaches this exact step.",
                "sources": [
                  "entity",
                  "context.activeTagIds",
                  "context.answers",
                  "merge_materials_estimate.result",
                  "global_rules.surcharges.dispatch_fee"
                ]
              }
            ],
            "ui_template_matrix": {
              "operation": "condition_map",
              "_note": "Determines UI layout. Evaluates top-down, first match wins. Corrected from the roadmap's original example: uses the NAMED flags from compute_variability_flags instead of a single chainIsQtyOnly boolean, specifically so the 3 real bypass_intake services with one genuine non-quantity question (high_ceiling_bulb_replacement, shower_head_replacement, tub_spout_replacement) are NOT routed into a template with no room to ask that question -- confirmed via direct check this session that those exact 3 services have complexity_tier:'skilled', not 'routine', ruling out a naive tier-based rule too.",
              "rules": [
                {
                  "if": {
                    "requires_furniture_selection": true
                  },
                  "then": {
                    "ui_template": "legacy_flow",
                    "_legacy_fn": "showIntakeQuestions"
                  },
                  "_note": "Archaeology Audit finding (confirmed via direct read of prefillSmartQuoteFromService): requires_furniture_selection and the isOther condition (default_tags includes #adhoc or #manual_review) BOTH completely bypass the curated-card/self-quote matrix today, diverting to the legacy showIntakeQuestions flow entirely -- a categorically different UI (a furniture item-picker grid, not a question card). Must be checked FIRST, before any confidence/chain-shape logic, exactly matching the legacy code's own early-return structure. Confirmed via direct data check: only furniture_assembly_flat_pack currently triggers this (requires_furniture_selection); the isOther/#adhoc/#manual_review condition is real, checkable code with zero services currently triggering it -- dormant today, not removed, since a future service could set those tags."
                },
                {
                  "if": {
                    "is_other_adhoc_service": true
                  },
                  "then": {
                    "ui_template": "legacy_flow",
                    "_legacy_fn": "showIntakeQuestions"
                  },
                  "_note": "Same legacy_flow bypass as requires_furniture_selection above, triggered instead by default_tags containing #adhoc or #manual_review. Confirmed dormant today (zero real services currently set either tag) but the condition is real, live code in getServiceProfile()/prefillSmartQuoteFromService -- kept as an explicit rule so a future service authored with these tags is correctly routed, not silently mishandled by the matrix's other rules."
                },
                {
                  "if": {
                    "chain_is_pure_quantity": true
                  },
                  "then": {
                    "ui_template": "self_quote",
                    "bypass_intake": true
                  },
                  "_note": "Pure quantity-only chain (or empty chain) -- the original, always-correct self-quote case."
                },
                {
                  "if": {
                    "chain_is_single_simple_question": true,
                    "behavior.bypass_intake": true
                  },
                  "then": {
                    "ui_template": "self_quote",
                    "bypass_intake": true
                  },
